<subSubSection id="BFE7095A13826C28776C5BDB40C09DE3" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="C5AD8A8989FEB3B73E6CB7FB8EA9C66C" pageNumber="60">
We treat the nominal species 
<taxonomicName id="EA586EE7D849514D1CCD73A734DF7D5D" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:4B12B657-3A11-4A78-A775-493F41DC6F7C" class="Actinopterygii" family="Siluridae" genus="Pterocryptis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pterocryptis gangelica Peters 1861:712" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="60" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="gangelica">Pterocryptis gangelica Peters, 1861</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="CBBEB270D01A57E55D40980383FD1C21" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:380DF4C5-0855-4EBC-B9E4-2E9F7554D469" class="Actinopterygii" family="Siluridae" genus="Silurus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Silurus afghana Günther 1864:34" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="60" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="afghana">
Silurus afghana 
<normalizedToken id="1A6258CD99CC1247FB4768C5BC42E83D" originalValue="Günther">Guenther</normalizedToken>
, 1864
</taxonomicName>
, both of which are known from the Brahmaputra and Ganges River drainages in the northern part of the Indian subcontinent as conspecific. 
<taxonomicName id="4CB8AC812C75D2A0C39ABA4A62E83701" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:3885C1A0-95D6-4FDB-8674-45214D2C4EE6" class="Actinopterygii" family="Siluridae" genus="Pterocryptis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pterocryptis Peters 1861:712" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="60" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pterocryptis</taxonomicName>
material from northern India is poorly represented in collections and we could not distinguish between the small amount of material identified as either of the two nominal species. Kobayakawa (1989) diagnosed 
<taxonomicName id="EEF5D83026B21A7E9D954257CCB4120E" class="Actinopterygii" family="Siluridae" genus="Pterocryptis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="60" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="afghana">P. afghana</taxonomicName>
as possessing tubercles on the snout, but our examination shows that tubercles are present on the snouts of all 
<taxonomicName id="B855AB13C143FC3146A7D47AB6D05DD3" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:3885C1A0-95D6-4FDB-8674-45214D2C4EE6" class="Actinopterygii" family="Siluridae" genus="Pterocryptis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pterocryptis Peters 1861:712" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="60" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pterocryptis</taxonomicName>
species, although the tubercles are often small and may be obscured by a thick layer of congealed mucus in preserved material. Furthermore, the tubercles are easily damaged (e.g. when we attempted to remove the layer of congealed mucus by rubbing), making it more difficult to study this character. In summary, it is possible that tubercle shape may be useful in diagnosing 
<taxonomicName id="CEF1998AD45FD69508C4BB0E06E7C2DA" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:3885C1A0-95D6-4FDB-8674-45214D2C4EE6" class="Actinopterygii" family="Siluridae" genus="Pterocryptis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pterocryptis Peters 1861:712" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="60" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pterocryptis</taxonomicName>
species, but its worth could not be fully assessed in our study. We note, however, that tubercle shape has been used as diagnostic characters in other catfish groups, most notably in sisorids (Mo &amp; Chu, 1986) and mochokids (Roberts, 1989; Ng, 2004); its utility as a diagnostic character for silurids warrants further investigation. The tubercles presumably enlarge during breeding, as is the case with other ostariophysans (Wiley &amp; Collette, 1970), but we do not understand enough of the biology of these fishes to be fully certain.
</paragraph>
